18. Similiter. The line of Vv'yclif's argument runs thus: The act of sight, as itis elicited in our brain, gives us awareness of the colour seen, independently of its size. Suppose this colour to be a white surface; each point that is white goes to make up the intensity of this awareness Now if it were really composed of intensive parts, each point (of which there is an infinite multitude) contributing a certain intensity to the act, this act would be infinitely intense. To each point there would correspond a certain intensive part. —— The adversaries would no doubt answer that the intensity contributed by each point of the sur- face is infinitely small.
